{"title_page": "Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle (EIFV)\n| image=\n|caption=\n|origin= [[Egypt]]\n|type= [[Infantry fighting vehicle]]\n|is_vehicle= yes\n|service= trials in 1997\n|used_by= [[Egyptian Army]]\n|wars=\n|designer= [[BAE Systems]]\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Egyptian Tank Factory, [[Arab Organization for Industrialization]]\n|unit_cost= $311,000\n|production_date= 1996\n|number= 1\n|variants=\n|length= 5.26 m\n|width= 2.82 m\n|height= 2.5 m\n|weight= 17.7 tons\n|suspension= torsion bar\n|speed= 66 km/h\n|vehicle_range= 482 km\n|primary_armament= 25 mm [[M242]] Chain Gun <br/> [[BGM-71 TOW|BGM-71 TOW II]]\n|secondary_armament= 7.62 mm [[FN MAG]]\n|armour= [[Aluminum]]\n|engine= Detroit Diesel 6V53TIA electronically controlled\n|crew= 3+7\n|engine_power= 400 hp at 2800 rpm\n|transmission= [[Torque converter|Hydrokinetic]]\n|fuel_capacity= 454 liters\n|clearance=\n|pw_ratio= 20.0 hp/ton\n}}\n\nThe '''Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle (EIFV)''', also known as '''Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light (IFVL)''', is an Egyptian modification of the [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier]]. It is a hybrid, based on an enlarged M113 chassis equipped with the complete two-man power-operated turret of the [[M2 Bradley]] [[Infantry Fighting Vehicle|IFV]].<ref name=\"BAEspecs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifvcharac.html|title=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light Specifications|publisher=[[BAE Systems]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2000|archive-url=https://archive.is/20020204103728/http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifvcharac.html|archive-date=2002-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BAE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifv.html|title=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light|publisher=[[BAE Systems]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2000|archive-url=https://archive.is/20020204074556/http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifv.html|archive-date=2002-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref> The EIFV never entered production for [[Egyptian Army]].<ref name=\"janesAPC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/articles/Janes-Armour-and-Artillery/BAE-Systems-Ground-Systems-Division-Infantry-Fighting-Vehicle-Light-United-States.html|title=BAE Systems Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light|publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2007-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425052253/http://www.janes.com/articles/Janes-Armour-and-Artillery/BAE-Systems-Ground-Systems-Division-Infantry-Fighting-Vehicle-Light-United-States.html|archive-date=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe EIFV was originally developed by [[BAE Systems]], Ground Systems Division under contract to the Egyptian Ministry of Defense. It was developed to be a conversion of the M113, of which the Egyptian Army has a total of 2,650, as well as an additional 1,200 [[AIFV]]s (modified M113s), but it can also be produced as new vehicles. Design activities first commenced in 1995, and the first prototype was assembled in the Egyptian Military Plant 200 where assembly of the [[M1 Abrams]] is carried out for the Egyptian Army. The first prototype was completed by Egyptian Military Plant 200 in 1996 and performance validation trials were completed in mid-1997. The EIFV has not entered production.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/><ref name=\"BAE\"/>\n\n==Description==\nThe EIFV has three crewman, and can carry six soldiers, who enter the vehicle via a rear drop ramp. The driver is seated at the left front of the hull with the engine compartment to his right. The driver has a single-piece pop-up hatch cover which rotates over the engine cooling air intake grill when open, and is provided with four, day periscopes for observation.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/> The commander and the gunner are both positioned in the turret itself, and a hatch is provided for the commander on the turret roof.\n\n===Armor===\nThe M113 chassis is enlarged to accommodate several modifications and to allow for more armor to be added. The hull of the EIFV is of all-welded 5083 aluminum armour which provides protection from small arms fire and shell splinters, able to defeat armour-piercing projectiles up to 14.5&nbsp;mm in calibre over a 360\u00b0 arc of attack.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/> Aluminum provides protection similar to that of steel armor while keeping the vehicle lightweight. An armor upgrade package produced by the [[Arab Organization for Industrialization|AOI]] can significantly enhance the armor on the EIFV even further, allowing it to withstand armor-piercing 23&nbsp;mm rounds, without sacrificing the vehicle's mobility. Optional upgrades for the vehicle include air conditioning, NBC protection and firing ports.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aoi.com.eg/aoi_eng/milit_new/vehicle/m113.htm |title=Arab Organization for Industrialization |access-date=2009-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624115704/http://www.aoi.com.eg/aoi_eng/milit_new/vehicle/m113.htm |archive-date=2007-06-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Maneuverability===\nTo cope with the increased size and armor of the vehicle, a more powerful 400&nbsp;hp Detroit Diesel 6V53TIA turbocharged/aftercooled diesel engine is installed in place of the original 275&nbsp;hp engine on the M113, giving a power-to-weight ratio of 20&nbsp;hp/ton. This is coupled to an Allison X200 cross-drive, four-speed [[Torque converter|Hydrokinetic transmission]]. As a result of the longer chassis and improved engine a sixth road wheel is added (the M113 only has five). As an option the vehicle can be of 350&nbsp;hp only. The modifications allows the EIFV to keep up in terms of speed and mobility with modern tanks such as the [[M1 Abrams|M1A1/A2 Abrams]], which are used by the Egyptian Army, despite the added weight. The vehicle can traverse [[Grade (slope)|slopes]] up to 80%, side slopes of 40%, trenches 2200&nbsp;mm wide, and vertical obstacles with a height of 710&nbsp;mm.<ref name=\"BAEspecs\"/>\n\n===Armament===\nThe [[M2 Bradley]] turret provides the EIFV with considerable firepower on a cheap M113 chassis, and allows it to engage personnel, armored vehicles and tanks, as well as low flying targets and helicopters. It has the same fire control and stabilization features on the M2 Bradley. The armament consists of the 25&nbsp;mm [[M242 Bushmaster|M242]] [[chain gun]] with 800 rounds and an effective range of 3000 m, and a coaxial [[7.62 mm caliber|7.62 mm]] machine gun with 2,100 rounds. Using armor-piercing rounds, the chain gun can engage armored vehicles and tanks. The turret also has a two-tube TOW launcher, capable of launching [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW II]] [[ATGM]] missiles, which can destroy most tanks at a maximum range of 3750 m, enabling the vehicle to be used in an [[Anti-tank warfare|anti tank role]]. The only major drawback is that the missiles can only be launched when the vehicle is stationary. In addition to the two missiles in the launcher are four more missiles, stowed away inside the vehicle. The turret is standard equipped with [[Infrared homing|passive IR]] and [[thermal imaging]] equipment.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/><ref name=\"BAEspecs\"/><ref name=\"BAE\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113 APC]]\n*[[AIFV]]\n*[[Armoured warfare]]\n*[[Infantry Fighting Vehicle]]\n\n[[Category:Armoured fighting vehicles of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Tracked infantry fighting vehicles|*]]\n[[Category:Armoured fighting vehicles of the post\u2013Cold War period]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle (EIFV)\n| image=\n|caption=\n|origin= [[Egypt]]\n|type= [[Infantry fighting vehicle]]\n|is_vehicle= yes\n|service= trials in 1997\n|used_by= [[Egyptian Army]]\n|wars=\n|designer= [[BAE Systems]]\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Egyptian Tank Factory, [[Arab Organization for Industrialization]]\n|unit_cost= $311,000\n|production_date= 1996\n|number= 1\n|variants=\n|length= 5.26 m\n|width= 2.82 m\n|height= 2.5 m\n|weight= 17.7 tons\n|suspension= torsion bar\n|speed= 66 km/h\n|vehicle_range= 482 km\n|primary_armament= 25 mm [[M242]] Chain Gun <br/> [[BGM-71 TOW|BGM-71 TOW II]]\n|secondary_armament= 7.62 mm [[FN MAG]]\n|armour= [[Aluminum]]\n|engine= Detroit Diesel 6V53TIA electronically controlled\n|crew= 3+7\n|engine_power= 400 hp at 2800 rpm\n|transmission= [[Torque converter|Hydrokinetic]]\n|fuel_capacity= 454 liters\n|clearance=\n|pw_ratio= 20.0 hp/ton\n}}\n\nThe '''Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle (EIFV)''', also known as '''Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light (IFVL)''', is an Egyptian modification of the [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier]]. It is a hybrid, based on an enlarged M113 chassis equipped with the complete two-man power-operated turret of the [[M2 Bradley]] [[Infantry Fighting Vehicle|IFV]].<ref name=\"BAEspecs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifvcharac.html|title=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light Specifications|publisher=[[BAE Systems]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2000|archive-url=https://archive.is/20020204103728/http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifvcharac.html|archive-date=2002-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BAE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifv.html|title=Egyptian Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light|publisher=[[BAE Systems]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2000|archive-url=https://archive.is/20020204074556/http://www.uniteddefense.com/www.m113.com/eifv.html|archive-date=2002-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref> The EIFV never entered production for [[Egyptian Army]].<ref name=\"janesAPC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/articles/Janes-Armour-and-Artillery/BAE-Systems-Ground-Systems-Division-Infantry-Fighting-Vehicle-Light-United-States.html|title=BAE Systems Infantry Fighting Vehicle Light|publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]]|accessdate=2009-01-29|date=2007-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425052253/http://www.janes.com/articles/Janes-Armour-and-Artillery/BAE-Systems-Ground-Systems-Division-Infantry-Fighting-Vehicle-Light-United-States.html|archive-date=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe EIFV was originally developed by [[BAE Systems]], Ground Systems Division under contract to the Egyptian Ministry of Defense. It was developed to be a conversion of the M113, of which the Egyptian Army has a total of 2,650, as well as an additional 1,200 [[AIFV]]s (modified M113s), but it can also be produced as new vehicles. Design activities first commenced in 1995, and the first prototype was assembled in the Egyptian Military Plant 200 where assembly of the [[M1 Abrams]] is carried out for the Egyptian Army. The first prototype was completed by Egyptian Military Plant 200 in 1996 and performance validation trials were completed in mid-1997. The EIFV has not entered production.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/><ref name=\"BAE\"/>\n\n==Description==\nThe EIFV has three crewman, and can carry six soldiers, who enter the vehicle via a rear drop ramp. The driver is seated at the left front of the hull with the engine compartment to his right. The driver has a single-piece pop-up hatch cover which rotates over the engine cooling air intake grill when open, and is provided with four, day periscopes for observation.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/> The commander and the gunner are both positioned in the turret itself, and a hatch is provided for the commander on the turret roof.\n\n===Armor===\nThe M113 chassis is enlarged to accommodate several modifications and to allow for more armor to be added. The hull of the EIFV is of all-welded 5083 aluminum armour which provides protection from small arms fire and shell splinters, able to defeat armour-piercing projectiles up to 14.5&nbsp;mm in calibre over a 360\u00b0 arc of attack.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/> Aluminum provides protection similar to that of steel armor while keeping the vehicle lightweight. An armor upgrade package produced by the [[Arab Organization for Industrialization|AOI]] can significantly enhance the armor on the EIFV even further, allowing it to withstand armor-piercing 23&nbsp;mm rounds, without sacrificing the vehicle's mobility. Optional upgrades for the vehicle include air conditioning, NBC protection and firing ports.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aoi.com.eg/aoi_eng/milit_new/vehicle/m113.htm |title=Arab Organization for Industrialization |access-date=2009-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624115704/http://www.aoi.com.eg/aoi_eng/milit_new/vehicle/m113.htm |archive-date=2007-06-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Maneuverability===\nTo cope with the increased size and armor of the vehicle, a more powerful 400&nbsp;hp Detroit Diesel 6V53TIA turbocharged/aftercooled diesel engine is installed in place of the original 275&nbsp;hp engine on the M113, giving a power-to-weight ratio of 20&nbsp;hp/ton. This is coupled to an Allison X200 cross-drive, four-speed [[Torque converter|Hydrokinetic transmission]]. As a result of the longer chassis and improved engine a sixth road wheel is added (the M113 only has five). As an option the vehicle can be of 350&nbsp;hp only. The modifications allows the EIFV to keep up in terms of speed and mobility with modern tanks such as the [[M1 Abrams|M1A1/A2 Abrams]], which are used by the Egyptian Army, despite the added weight. The vehicle can travers [[Grade (slope)|slopes]] up to 80%, side slopes of 40%, trenches 2200&nbsp;mm wide, and vertical obstacles with a height of 710&nbsp;mm.<ref name=\"BAEspecs\"/>\n\n===Armament===\nThe [[M2 Bradley]] turret provides the EIFV with considerable firepower on a cheap M113 chassis, and allows it to engage personnel, armored vehicles and tanks, as well as low flying targets and helicopters. It has the same fire control and stabilization features on the M2 Bradley. The armament consists of the 25&nbsp;mm [[M242 Bushmaster|M242]] [[chain gun]] with 800 rounds and an effective range of 3000 m, and a coaxial [[7.62 mm caliber|7.62 mm]] machine gun with 2,100 rounds. Using armor-piercing rounds, the chain gun can engage armored vehicles and tanks. The turret also has a two-tube TOW launcher, capable of launching [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW II]] [[ATGM]] missiles, which can destroy most tanks at a maximum range of 3750 m, enabling the vehicle to be used in an [[Anti-tank warfare|anti tank role]]. The only major drawback is that the missiles can only be launched when the vehicle is stationary. In addition to the two missiles in the launcher are four more missiles, stowed away inside the vehicle. The turret is standard equipped with [[Infrared homing|passive IR]] and [[thermal imaging]] equipment.<ref name=\"janesAPC\"/><ref name=\"BAEspecs\"/><ref name=\"BAE\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113 APC]]\n*[[AIFV]]\n*[[Armoured warfare]]\n*[[Infantry Fighting Vehicle]]\n\n[[Category:Armoured fighting vehicles of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Tracked infantry fighting vehicles|*]]\n[[Category:Armoured fighting vehicles of the post\u2013Cold War period]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManeuverability:Typo fixing, replaced: travers \u2192 traverse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_Infantry_Fighting_Vehicle"}
{"title_page": "Bep Thomas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Bep Thomas\n| fullname            = Albert Rudolf Thomas\n| image               =\n| caption             =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1938|10|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| death_date          = <!-- Use {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1938|10|7|df=y}} if dead (death date followed by birth date) -->\n| death_place         =\n| otheroccupation     =\n| years1              = 1979\u20131989\n| league1             = [[Eredivisie]]\n| role1               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1981\u20131989\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Albert Rudolf \"Bep\" Thomas''' (born 7 October 1938) is a retired Dutch [[Association football|football]] referee.\n\n==Refereeing career==\nThomas began his refereeing career in [[Amsterdam]] before being assigned to officiate in the [[Eerste Divisie]]. In 1979, he was promoted to the [[Eredivisie]], where he officiated 248 matches. In 1981, Thomas was appointed as a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]].\n\nIn 1988, Thomas was chosen as a referee for [[UEFA Euro 1988]], where he officiated a [[UEFA Euro 1988 Group 1#Spain vs Denmark|group stage match]] between [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/report/em-1988-in-deutschland-gruppe-1-spanien-daenemark/ |title=Spain - Denmark 3:2 (EURO 1988 Germany, Group 1) |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThomas stopped officiating internationally and in the Eredivisie in 1989, before retiring from officiating in 1991.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee|albert-thomas|Albert Thomas}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|albert-rudolf-thomas/244933}}\n* {{WorldReferee.com|bep_thomas}}\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1988 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Bep}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 referees]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Bep Thomas\n| fullname            = Albert Rudolf Thomas\n| image               =\n| caption             =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1938|10|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| death_date          = <!-- Use {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1938|10|7|df=y}} if dead (death date followed by birth date) -->\n| death_place         =\n| otheroccupation     =\n| years1              = 1979\u20131989\n| league1             = [[Eredivisie]]\n| role1               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1981\u20131989\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n'''Albert Rudolf \"Bep\" Thomas''' (born 7 October 1938) is a retired Dutch [[Association football|football]] referee.\n\n==Refereeing career==\nThomas began his refereeing career in [[Amsterdam]] before being assigned to officiate in the [[Eerste Divisie]]. In 1979, he was promoted to the [[Eredivisie]], where he officiated 248 matches. In 1981, Thomas was appointed as a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]].\n\nIn 1988, Thomas was chosen as a referee for [[UEFA Euro 1988]], where he officiated a [[UEFA Euro 1988 Group 1#Spain vs Denmark|group stage match]] between [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/report/em-1988-in-deutschland-gruppe-1-spanien-daenemark/ |title=Spain - Denmark 3:2 (EURO 1988 Germany, Group 1) |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThomas stopped officiating internationally and in the Eredivisie in 1989, before retiring from officiating in 1991.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/albert-thomas/ Profile] at worldfootball.net\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1988 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Bep}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 referees]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bep_Thomas"}
